                    <h2>About RGB Color Spaces</h2>
                    <p>RGB (Red, Green, Blue) is an additive color model in which red, green, and blue light are added together in various ways to reproduce a broad array of colors.  The name comes from the three additive primary colors, red, green, and blue.  In the RGB color model, each color is represented by a value from 0 to 255, where 0 represents the absence of the color and 255 represents its maximum intensity.  RGB is widely used in digital displays, such as computer monitors and televisions.</p>

                    <h3>Why Use RGB?</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Digital Display Standard:</strong>  The primary color model for computer screens and other displays.</li>
                        <li><strong>Additive Color Mixing:</strong> Allows for the creation of a wide range of colors by combining red, green, and blue light.</li>
                        <li><strong>Direct Control:</strong> Offers precise control over the intensity of each color component.</li>
                    </ul>

